    "body": "### Problem\r\n\r\nWhen using pwsh as `&shell`, if the output generated by an external command contains colours, the command line doesn't correctly parse the escape sequences, which then pollute the output itself. Vim can correctly parse those escape sequences, and shows coloured text.\r\n\r\n### Steps to reproduce\r\n\r\nPrerequisites:\r\nCreate a file called `test.vim` containing the following code:\r\n```\r\nlet &shell = executable('pwsh') ? 'pwsh' : 'powershell'\r\nlet &shellcmdflag = '-NoLogo -ExecutionPolicy RemoteSigned -Command [Console]::InputEncoding=[Console]::OutputEncoding=[System.Text.UTF8Encoding]::new();$PSDefaultParameterValues[''Out-File:Encoding'']=''utf8'';Remove-Alias -Force -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue tee;'\r\nlet &shellredir = '2>&1 | %%{ \"$_\" } | Out-File %s; exit $LastExitCode'\r\nlet &shellpipe  = '2>&1 | %%{ \"$_\" } | tee %s; exit $LastExitCode'\r\nset shellquote= shellxquote=\r\n```\r\nand a `Microsoft.PowerShell_profile.ps1` (which should be placed in the appropriate location returned by `$PROFILE`) containing:\r\n```\r\n$PSReadLineOptions = @{\r\n    ContinuationPrompt  = \"${pspromptcolour}>> `e[0m\"\r\n    ViModeIndicator     = 'Script'\r\n    ViModeChangeHandler = $Function:OnViModeChange\r\n    EditMode            = 'Vi'\r\n    PredictionViewStyle = 'ListView'\r\n    PromptText          = \"${pspromptcolour}> \", 'x '\r\n    Colors              = @{\r\n        Selection              = \"`e[1;35m\"\r\n        ListPredictionSelected = \"`e[1;35m\"\r\n    }\r\n    AddToHistoryHandler = {\r\n        param($command)\r\n        if ($command -like ' *') {\r\n            return $false\r\n        }\r\n        elseif (@('exit', 'clear') -contains $command) {\r\n            return $false\r\n        }\r\n        else {\r\n            return $true\r\n        }\r\n    }\r\n}\r\n\r\nSet-PSReadLineOption @PSReadLineOptions\r\n```\r\n\r\n1. `nvim --clean`\r\n2. `:source .\\test.vim`\r\n3. ensure that `shell=pwsh`\r\n4. `:!pwd`\r\n\r\nThis process outputs:\r\n\r\n```\r\n^[[31;1mSet-PSReadLineOption: ^[[0mC:\\Users\\matteocoder\\Documents\\PowerShell\\Microsoft.PowerShell_profile.ps1:260^[[0m\r\n^[[31;1m^[[0m^[[36;1mLine |^[[0m\r\n^[[31;1m^[[0m^[[36;1m^[[36;1m 260 | ^[[0m ^[[36;1mSet-PSReadLineOption @PSReadLineOptions^[[0m\r\n^[[31;1m^[[0m^[[36;1m^[[36;1m^[[0m^[[36;1m^[[0m^[[36;1m     | ^[[31;1m ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~^[[0m\r\n^[[31;1m^[[0m^[[36;1m^[[36;1m^[[0m^[[36;1m^[[0m^[[36;1m^[[31;1m^[[31;1m^[[36;1m     | ^[[31;1mThe handle is invalid.^[[0m\r\n\r\n^[[32;1mPath^[[0m\r\n^[[32;1m----^[[0m\r\nC:\\Users\\matteocoder\r\n```\r\n\r\nThis test highlights another problem with the interaction between pwsh and neovim: for some reason, option splatting seems to fail. I don't know what the culprit is in this case, so I guess it would be better to discuss this aspect in a separate issue.\r\n\r\n### Expected behavior\r\n\r\nThe command line should display coloured text. I imagine this doesn't happen because PowerShell uses the backtick as the escape character rather than the traditional backslash.\r\n\r\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\r\n\r\nNVIM v0.10.0-dev-9dc4404 Build type: RelWithDebInfo LuaJIT 2.1.1697887905 Compilation: C:/Program Files (x86)/Microsoft Visual Studio/2019/Enterprise/VC/Tools/MSVC/14.29.30133/bin/Hostx64/x64/cl.exe /DWIN32 /D_WINDOWS /MD /Zi /O2 /Ob1  -W3 -wd4311 -wd4146 -wd4003 -wd4715 -DUNIT_TESTING -D_CRT_SECURE_NO_WARNINGS -D_CRT_NONSTDC_NO_DEPRECATE -D_WIN32_WINNT=0x0602 -DMSWIN -DINCLUDE_GENERATED_DECLARATIONS -DNVIM_TS_HAS_SET_MAX_START_DEPTH -ID:/a/neovim/neovim/.deps/usr/include/luajit-2.1 -ID:/a/neovim/neovim/.deps/usr/include -ID:/a/neovim/neovim/build/src/nvim/auto -ID:/a/neovim/neovim/build/include -ID:/a/neovim/neovim/build/cmake.config -ID:/a/neovim/neovim/src     system vimrc file: \"$VIM\\sysinit.vim\"   fall-back for $VIM: \"C:/Program Files (x86)/nvim/share/nvim\"\r\n\r\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\r\n\r\nno, Vim 9.0.2026\r\n\r\n### Operating system/version\r\n\r\nMicrosoft Windows 10.0.22621\r\n\r\n### Terminal name/version\r\n\r\nPowerShell 7.4.0-preview.6, Windows Terminal 1.18.2822.0\r\n\r\n### $TERM environment variable\r\n\r\nN/A\r\n\r\n### Installation\r\n\r\nwinget",
